by South Reinkalistan » Thu Mar 18, 2021 4:06 pm

Menschlicher Sternenstaat wrote:
South Reinkalistan wrote:why stop at your fleets? obliterate humanity itself and embrace the supremacy of the machine.


no

This is mainly because most people that attempt doing machine nations lack the actual context of "machine cognition", and how it would be most likely geared towards maximum self-preservation rather than the cliche "assimilate everything into a network" or "neutralization of organics" with no real utility.

I mean, the thing here is quite simple. Self-preservation as a root can provide a tonne of different options in the future for how self-preservation is interpreted. Most of even the cliche assimilation/murder bots do so under the pretext that this is seen as the best way to secure the existence of the machine consciousness. But I'm aware that this is mostly unrealistic and boring.

Generally however I fail to see how there being a series of cliches associated with machine nations - which, might I add, is the case with basically every concept - necessarily makes the entire concept bad. If anything, the overabundance of cliches presents a golden opportunity to subvert expectations and create something interesting.

Cliches aren't so bad insofar that they are just fillers where original content could be. The key to writing a good overarching narrative is, quite simply, taking where there would be these filler-cliches and packing them with as much juicy originality as possible. They also provide us - and this is where cliches matter - with a way to measure relative originality.

Nobody wants an unoriginal piece of trash, but nobody's going to blame you for slipping into a handful of tropes. It's all about balancing things and finding that nice happy little medium where you can crank out something special.

by The Troas Sector » Thu Mar 18, 2021 4:17 pm

South Reinkalistan wrote:
Menschlicher Sternenstaat wrote:
no

This is mainly because most people that attempt doing machine nations lack the actual context of "machine cognition", and how it would be most likely geared towards maximum self-preservation rather than the cliche "assimilate everything into a network" or "neutralization of organics" with no real utility.

I mean, the thing here is quite simple. Self-preservation as a root can provide a tonne of different options in the future for how self-preservation is interpreted. Most of even the cliche assimilation/murder bots do so under the pretext that this is seen as the best way to secure the existence of the machine consciousness. But I'm aware that this is mostly unrealistic and boring.

Generally however I fail to see how there being a series of cliches associated with machine nations - which, might I add, is the case with basically every concept - necessarily makes the entire concept bad. If anything, the overabundance of cliches presents a golden opportunity to subvert expectations and create something interesting.

A robot 'nation' that doesn't actually control any weapons/physical assets and that is instead a self-expanding botnet would be interesting. An AI that believes it needs to control as many computers as possible as to gain as much computing power as possible so that it can solve some 'mystery' of the universe that it was programmed to solve by its creators. It'd also be an interesting way to explore machine mechanics, as the AI goes rogue not to commit mass murder, but just in that its influence extends far outside of the original mission parameters envisioned by whoever created it as it needs that influence to 'finish the task' or whatever.

Probably a dumb idea but still, it could be interesting if someone with actual talent does it and actually makes it particularly interesting. It would still fit into the 'rogue AI' idea, but with a vastly different content as to subvert the traditional cliches.

The Troas Sector wrote:
A robot 'nation' that doesn't actually control any weapons/physical assets and that is instead a self-expanding botnet would be interesting. An AI that believes it needs to control as many computers as possible as to gain as much computing power as possible so that it can solve some 'mystery' of the universe that it was programmed to solve by its creators. It'd also be an interesting way to explore machine mechanics, as the AI goes rogue not to commit mass murder, but just in that its influence extends far outside of the original mission parameters envisioned by whoever created it as it needs that influence to 'finish the task' or whatever.


That idea, the first thing that came to my mind about that concept is the WAU from the game Soma. Yeah there are enemies in the game that are created by the WAU but they're mainly there to have enemies in the game and there's probably some weird lore explanation in the game but I don't remember it.

The WAU is the AI that runs the underwater science facility known as Pathos-II that the game takes place in. So when an asteroid kills literally everything on the land leaving the staff of Pathos-II the only humans left, they give it an objective to "Preserve Human Life".

The problem is that not only did they give the AI a blank check and broad authority on such an incredibly complex idea. It's so complex that the questions of "What does it mean to be Human?" and "What makes us "Us"?" are the two existential questions that the game is all about. But they were also kinda dumb as they gave no definitions of what things like, the Human Condition or what a human ought to be.

So of course it starts doing literally anything to keep a human "alive". It starts creating biomechanical parts that are connected to the station and connects it to injured people in a worse form of life support. It starts copying people's brain scans and puts them into robots. These robots also see their bodies as humans and to them they just experience what seemed to be a blackout when they get transferred. And if the damages are bad enough it might just turn a person onto a half-human/half-WAU abomination so they can survive.

It doesn't do any of this because it is Evil. It does this because it doesn't know what the line of what's no longer human. How can you tell where the line is that someone is no longer "Human"? Especially if you were never told there was line to be drawn in the first place.

Federal Spanish States wrote:
Kiu Ghesik wrote:Yeah, I'd definitely concur. I've just seen so many crystal dragon jesus- style "OOH OUR ELVES ARE MADE OUT OF SILICON" attempts to defy tropes in the sense that the writer is more or less a novice and very clearly interprets tropes as to be avoided like the plague rather than tools to be used sparingly and at the writer's discretion that I can't really not throw out that "tropes aren't always bad things" line whenever it comes up.


Call me wrong if I am, but doesn't TVTropes have a page that pretty much says "tropes are neither bad nor good, it's impossible to not write a story without at least using one, but don't go overboard with them, and instead, try to use them in new ways"?

And as someone who very frequents TVTropes for inspirations and, well, tropes, yes, I'm proud of that.

A few nations have already done that - Tropes are tools, not clichés to be avoided. Originality might be getting difficult, which is not the fault of your creativity - there's only so many ideas that we can have. Start appreciating your tropes and use them to further yourself.

A cliche only happens because often times, I'm not going to point fingers, but a nation's lore is 1:1 with RL nations or history or fiction, and there's no deviation.

You can totally have a Star Wars themed nation, but it would be a bit of a waste if you just copy-paste the Empire's history (and that would probably count as plagiarism if it is exactly the same).
